'''Lajos Simicska''' (born 28 January 1960) is a [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] businessman who was head of [[APEH (Hungary)|APEH]], Hungary's internal revenue service, in 1998–1999 during the first administration of [[Viktor Orbán]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theorangefiles.hu/lajos-simicskakozgep/|title=Lajos Simicska|date=14 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> He had extensive media interests with the daily ''[[Magyar Nemzet]]'', the radio station [[Lánchíd Rádió]], the weekly magazine [[Heti Válasz]] and the television network [[Hír TV]]. After having disagreements with the Hungarian Prime Minister [[Viktor Orbán]], Simicska expressed his support for the radical party [[Jobbik]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-media-politics/hungarys-top-news-portal-passed-to-entities-close-to-pm-orbans-adversary-idUSKBN17M2FL|title=Hungary's top news portal passed to entities close to PM Orban's adver|date=20 April 2017|publisher=|via=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Day | first1=Matthew |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/hungary/11499564/Viktor-Orban-denies-being-communist-informer-during-days-of-one-party-state-in-Hungary.html|title=Viktor Orban denies being communist informer during days of one-party state in Hungary| date=27 March 2015|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>http://www.thenewage.co.za/153710-1020-53-Feud_between_Hungarian_PM_oligarch_deepens_with_informant_charge {{dead link|date=December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbj.hu/politics/simicska-orban-was-communist-informer_93801|title=Simicska: Orbán was communist informer|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hungarytoday.hu/cikk/total-media-war-simicska-hints-orban-might-reporting-29780|title="Total Media War" - Simicska Hints Orbán Might Have Been "Reporting" - Hungary Today|publisher=}}</ref>

Simicska shut down his daily newspaper ''Magyar Nemzet'' after 80 years in print, and Lánchíd Rádió in response to Prime Minister Viktor Orbán winning a third consecutive parliamentary supermajority in the [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 2018|2018 parliamentary election]]. Shortly afterward, Simicska closed or sold all of his remaining holdings.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Walker | first1=Shaun | title=Emboldened Viktor Orbán Cracks Down on Friend Turned Foe | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/12/orban-tightens-grip-on-hungary-as-oppositions-power-wanes | date=12 August 2018 | publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' | accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Orban Loyalists Take Control of Prominent Hungarian News Channel | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-orban-media/orban-loyalists-take-control-of-prominent-hungarian-news-channel-idUSKBN1KM4VT | date=1 August 2018 | publisher=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>

